Abstract

Throughout 2021, starting in February, a Burmese military staged coup has caused deep unrest in Myanmar leading to the detainment, imprisonment, and killing of many civilians and opposition forces. Furthermore, this coup toppled the government and removed Aung San Suu Kyi, the civilian leader, and other elected officials from power. This report uses data aggregated by the Assistance Association for Political Prisoners (AAPP) to characterize detainment information since the coup. The datasets we are provided show the conflicts in Myanmar, and the detained, deceased, and imprisoned individuals. We do a township-level analysis of this data by cleaning the data, and merging the data on the township name. Then we run a Fisher’s test to understand the impacts of military conflicts on the fatality rate in townships. We run two regressions to understand if the type of conflict has an influence on the number of detainees per conflict. We also try to see if there is a relationship between age and the number of detainees by conflict. However, our results show a lack of consistency in the statistically significant variables. Smaller townships are facing higher rates of detainees, and more violence. This could be that these regions are easier for violent agents to control, and therefore easier to attack. We have to consider that this real-world data is imperfect, and can cause flaws in our process. Since this situation is a human rights violation, it has international implications. Therefore, we need to be somewhat careful in the way that this data is being used and presented.

Introduction

This analysis relies on the following five datasets:
- detained.csv.gz - the gzipped csv file concerning detainees (AAPP)
- imprisoned.csv.gz - the file concerning those sentenced (AAPP)
- fallen.csv - the file concerning those deceased civilians from conflict with the military (AAPP)
- MIMU_Baseline... .xlsm - an Excel macro file containing historical Myanmar indicators at the township level (MIMU)
- conflicts.csv.gz - a derived dataset on conflicts and protests in Myanmar in 2021 (ACLED)

Methods

Data Cleaning

The following steps were taken to clean the detainees dataset for further statistical analysis:
- Clean the Sex column to contain only values of “M” or “F.” We did this because we are uncertain how to interpret a value of “LGBT” in the context of this data, and because some other values have unclean data.
- Clean the Region/State column text.
- Use lubridate to reformate the Date of Arrest column and extract the month value.
- Clean the Township column text.

Data Merging

In this section, the leven & apply_leven functions are defined and used to merge the previously discussed datasets on the township level. For this there are several steps that need to be taken. These steps include:
- First, we apply the apply_leven function to our datasets to give each observation an appropriate township name from the MIMU dataset. This will be the column for later joining datasets together.
- Then, we join the datasets together using the townships columns.
- Next, we prepare this combined data for analysis by using map() functions on the nested data to get indicator summary measures at the township levels.
- We then use the conflicts and MIMU datasets to create indicators at the township level that we can use in further statistical analysis of the initial datasets: detained, fallen, and imprisoned. - Finally, we merge our indicators with these covariate values from the conflicts and MIMU datasets. This will serve as the data for our modelling and other analysis.

# Defining leven & apply_leven functions for future dataset merging
leven = function(x, y, k=0, ignore.case=T) {
  data.frame(y=y) %>%
    as_tibble() %>%
    
    # compute Levenshtein distance for string x for each y
    mutate(distance = utils::adist(x, y, 
                                   ignore.case=ignore.case) %>% .[1,]) %>%
    
    # keep y's within k of the best match
    filter(distance <= min(distance, na.rm=T) + k) %>%
    mutate(distance.per.char = distance/nchar(y))
}

# Use `leven` for string *vectors* `x` and `y`
apply_leven = function(x, y, k=0, distance.threshold=0.3, ignore.case=F) {
  data.frame(x=x) %>%
    # get potential matches for each x as a list of tibbles
    mutate(leven.df = map(x, ~ leven(.x, y=y,
                                     k=k, ignore.case=ignore.case))
    ) %>%
    unnest(everything()) %>%
    mutate(is.match=distance.per.char < distance.threshold) %>%
    
    # order by best match
    arrange(distance.per.char) %>%
    
    # keep the best match per `x`
    group_by(x) %>% 
    slice(1) %>%  
    ungroup() %>%
    
    # convert non-matches to Other
    mutate(y = ifelse(is.match, y, "Other"))  
}
# Apply leven function to each dataset (detained, fallen, imprisoned) with unique township names
# Join to the MIMU township names

# For the MIMU dataset, nest the dataframe to get unique townships & their total population
township.sizes = sector.nest %>% 
  filter(Indicator_Name=="Population size", 
         Indicator_Type=="Total", 
         str_detect(Source_Name, "Census")) %>%
  unnest(everything())

# Detainees Dataset
joined.det = detained %>%
  inner_join(apply_leven(detained$Township, 
                         township.sizes$Township_Name,
                         distance.threshold=0.28),
             by=c("Township"="x")
  ) %>%
  rename(detainee_township=Township, MIMU_township=y) %>%
  filter(is.match == TRUE)


# Fallen Dataset
joined.fal = fallen1 %>%
  inner_join(apply_leven(fallen1$Township, 
                         township.sizes$Township_Name,
                         distance.threshold=0.28),
             by=c("Township"="x")
  ) %>%
  rename(fallen_township=Township, MIMU_township=y) %>%
  filter(is.match == TRUE)


# Imprisoned Dataset
joined.imp = imprisoned1 %>%
  inner_join(apply_leven(imprisoned1$Township, 
                         township.sizes$Township_Name,
                         distance.threshold=1),
             by=c("Township"="x")
  ) %>%
  rename(imprisoned_township=Township, MIMU_township=y) %>%
  filter(is.match == TRUE)

# For each dataset (detained, fallen, imprisoned) nest each dataframe to get the unique townships
nested.det = joined.det %>% 
  nest(det.data=-MIMU_township)

nested.fal = joined.fal %>% 
  nest(fal.data=-MIMU_township)

nested.imp = joined.imp %>% 
  nest(imp.data=-MIMU_township)

# Joining the detainees dataset to the fallen dataset (using left join) to preserve most the max amount of rows
joined.data <- left_join(nested.det, nested.fal, by=c("MIMU_township"))

joined.data <- left_join(joined.data, nested.imp, by = c("MIMU_township"))

# Joining the imprisoned dataset to the already joined datasets (using left join)

# Merging (and cleaning) the `detained`, `imprisoned`, and `fallen` data, for potential comparative analysis of detainment and violence against civilians (township level) 
joined.data.indicators <- joined.data %>%
  mutate(Imprisoned = map_dbl(imp.data, ~ NROW(.x)), 
         Detained = map_dbl(det.data, ~NROW(.x)), 
         Fallen = map_dbl(fal.data, ~NROW(.x)), 
         Total = Imprisoned + Fallen + Detained, # not sure if we will use this, not valid measure
         Prop.Detained.Male = map_dbl(det.data, ~ sum(.x$Sex == 'M', na.rm=T)) / Detained
         ) %>%
  arrange(desc(Total)) %>%
  select(MIMU_township, Imprisoned, Detained, Fallen, Total, Prop.Detained.Male,
         det.data, imp.data, fal.data) %>%
  arrange(desc(Detained))

# Nesting conflicts by townships
# Join conflicts dataset to the MIMU township names
# Extracting noteworthy indicators for future statistical analysis 

covariate.indicators <- conflicts %>% 
  # nesting
  nest(conflicts.data=-c(township)) %>%
  # merging with the detainee_township, MIMU_township mapper
  inner_join(apply_leven(.$township,
                         township.sizes$Township_Name,
                         distance.threshold=0.28),
             by=c("township"="x")
  ) %>%
  rename(conflicts_township=township, MIMU_township=y) %>%
  left_join(township.sizes, by=c("MIMU_township"="Township_Name")) %>%
  rename(Population.thousands = Value) %>% # NOTE the renamed column since it's just population
  select(MIMU_township, Population.thousands, conflicts.data) %>%
  mutate(conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ nrow(.x)),
         deadly.conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['fatalities']]>0)),
         prop.conflicts.deadly = deadly.conflicts / conflicts,
         fatalities = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['fatalities']])),
         Military.conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['perpetrator_group']]=='Military')),
         Rebels.conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['perpetrator_group']]=='Rebels')),
         Political.militia.conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['perpetrator_group']]=='Political Militia')),
         Communal.militia.conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['perpetrator_group']]=='Communal Militia')),
         Rioters.conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['perpetrator_group']]=='Rioters')),
         Protesters.conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['perpetrator_group']]=='Protesters')),
         Civilians.conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['perpetrator_group']]=='Civilians')),
         Other.conflicts = map_dbl(conflicts.data, ~ sum(.x[['perpetrator_group']]=='Other')))

model.data <- joined.data.indicators %>%
  left_join(covariate.indicators, by=c("MIMU_township")) %>%
  mutate(Imprisoned.per.thousand = Imprisoned / Population.thousands,
         Detained.per.thousand = Detained / Population.thousands,
         Fallen.per.thousand = Fallen / Population.thousands) %>%
  arrange(desc(Population.thousands))

Bivariate/Multivariate Table

Table 5 displays the number of lethal conflicts (conflicts in which there is at least one fatality) for each perpetrator group and target group combination.
The left column displays the perpetrator group of each deadly conflicts while the rest of the columns depict the target of these conflicts.

conflicts %>%
  group_by(perpetrator_group, target_group) %>%
  summarize(lethal_conflicts = sum(fatalities>0), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  rename(`Perpetrator Group` = perpetrator_group) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = target_group, values_from = lethal_conflicts, values_fill = 0) %>%
  kable(caption = 'Table 5: Number of Lethal Conflicts by Perpetrator Group')
Table 5: Number of Lethal Conflicts by Perpetrator Group
Perpetrator Group Sole Action Military Rebels Political Militia Communal Militia Civilians Other Rioters Protesters
Military 1 13 150 222 1 520 0 0 0
Rebels 0 97 10 0 0 10 0 0 0
Political Militia 8 401 1 55 0 596 0 0 0
Communal Militia 0 0 0 0 0 1 0 0 0
Rioters 0 33 0 0 0 2 0 2 0
Protesters 0 140 0 1 0 0 0 1 0
Civilians 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0
Other 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0

In Table 5, we see that there is a high incidence of lethal conflicts between the Military and Political Militias targeting each other, as well as cases where these two groups target Civilians. This table simply demonstrates whether a death occurred in a conflict. It is important to note that a death in an interaction between a perpetrator and a target does not necessarily indicate to a death in the target group but rather that a death occurred at all. It is also notable that “sole action” from both Military and Political Militia groups lead to lethal conflicts. These data points merit investigation because, in events of death, it is important not to miss out on a valid interaction between two groups and data should thus reflect a target group in these cases.

Univariate Descriptive Figure

The fallen dataset has information on the ages of individuals killed in Myanmar during the last year in events related to the coup and political unrest. There were 1208 individuals killed. Of these individuals, 904 of the observations contained data on the age of the killed individuals. These individuals ranged in age from 1 to 90 years old, with a median age of 30 and mean age of 32. Many of those killed fell between the ages of 15 and 40 (Figure 1).

Bivariate/Multivariate Descriptive Figure

In the conflicts dataset, all conflicts are assigned codes for the group to which the conflict perpetrator and conflict target belong. Many conflicts have no specific target, in which case the conflict is coded as “sole action” of the perpetrator. There are 8 perpetrator groups to which the conflicts are ascribed, including “Military,” “Protesters,” and “Political Militia.”
We can view the reported deaths resulting from conflicts from different perpetrators and perpetrator groups, but it is important to note that these fatalities do not necessarily belong to the conflict’s “target” group. For example, in conflicts instigated by protesters or rioters, it may be the case that most fatalities belonged to those groups. On the other hand, in the case of military or militia action, the deaths might have mostly occurred in the conflict target group.

# Sum the non-military conflicts, and calculate the fatalities per thousand. 
hypothesis <- model.data %>%
  mutate(Fatalities.per.thousand = fatalities / Population.thousands, 
         non_military = Rebels.conflicts + Political.militia.conflicts + 
           Communal.militia.conflicts + Rioters.conflicts + Protesters.conflicts
          + Civilians.conflicts + Other.conflicts) %>%
  select(MIMU_township, Military.conflicts, non_military, Fatalities.per.thousand)

ggplot(data = hypothesis, aes(x = Fatalities.per.thousand)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  xlab("Fatalities (per 1000)") + 
  ylab("Count") +
  ggtitle("Figure 4: Count of Fatalities (per 1000)") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5))

# Create a table with level, if the fatalities per thousand is high or low
hyp.table <- hypothesis %>%
  mutate(level = case_when(Fatalities.per.thousand >= 0.5 ~ "High", 
                           Fatalities.per.thousand < 0.5 ~ "Low")) %>%
  group_by(level) %>%
  summarize(Military = sum(Military.conflicts), 
            Non_Military = sum(non_military))
# Take the values from hyp.table to create a matrix for the Fisher test
hyp.table

Townships with high (greater than 0.5 fatalities/thousand) fatality rate, have higher odds of having a larger number of military conflicts, compared to non-military conflicts. Using our Fisher’s Exact Test for Count Data, high fatality townships had a 2 times greater odds of having more military conflicts than low fatality townships. These results are statistically significant, with a p-value of 0, which is less than the alpha value of 0.05.

Regression Diagnostics 1

The following four plots are important diagnostic tools in assessing whether the linear model is appropriate.

# Diagnostics Plots
plot(det.lm)

Interpretation of Linear Regression 1

Looking at the plot, we see some of the variables are correlated. In particular, Military.conflicts and Political.militia.conflicts demonstrate a correlation of 0.625938. Furthermore, Protesters.conflicts and Political.militia.conflicts demonstrate a correlation of 0.4406758. For this reason, Political.militia.conflicts was removed from this linear regression and the linear model was updated.

Although the removal did not change the regression drastically, it increased the statistical significance of the already statistically significant Rioters.conflicts to a p-value of 8.43^{-4} and of Protesters.conflicts to a p-value of 4.06^{-4}. Additionally, the statistical significance of Population.thousands increased to a p-value of 9.36^{-4}.

Now, looking at those variables in more detail, all else being equal between two states, a 1-unit increase in Population.thousands appears to be associated with a 2.61^{-4} decrease in Detained.per.thousand. On the other hand, a 1-unit increase in Rioters.conflicts appears to be associated with a 0.019868 increase in Detained.per.thousand while a a 1-unit increase in Protesters.conflicts appears to be associated with a 0.001085 increase in Detained.per.thousand.

We observe our linear regression model to be appropriate based on the Residuals vs. Fitted plot. There we can identify that the residuals have constant variance when plotted against fitted values. Furthermore, we can see that the residuals and fitted values are uncorrelated. The p-values for this model are believable, as seen in the QQ Plot where the residuals from the regression are approximately normally distributed. Similarly to the Residuals vs. Fitted plot, there are no discernible trends noticeable in the Scale-location plot. Only one of the points on the Residuals vs Leverage plot appears to be an outlier.

plot(det.lm2)

Interpretation for Linear Regression 2

For this regression, we decided to add the proportion of male detainees into our previous regression. We wanted to see if there was a relationship between the proportion males had an affect on the number of detainees per thousand of population. Similar to the last regression, we tested for collinearity to get statistically significant coefficients.

Our assessment of collinearity showed that Political.militia.conflicts and military.conflicts were highly collinear, therefore the former is not included in our regression. We used the pair plot to see if there are any highly collinear variables for this regression. The proportion of males and military conflicts although appeared highly correlated, was not with a correlation of 0.0411372. We included both of these in our model. However, military conflicts and protester conflicts we’re relatively collinear, with a correlation of 0.4909195. Therefore, we removed Protesters.conflicts to see if this changed the significance of our variables in the regression.

The only statistically significant variables were Population.thousands (p = 0.006). Holding all other variables constant, every one unit increase of Population.thousands results in a 2.2022771^{-4} decrease in the number of detainees in a township per 1000 of population.

The other statistically significant variable is Rioters.conflicts (p = 0). Holding all other variables constant, every one unit increase in the number of Rioters.conflicts results in a 0.0263832 increase in the number of detainees in a township per 1000 of population.

These numbers are not particularly interpretable because the units for each variable (including our target variable) are in different proportions (e.g. detainees per 1000). All other variables are not statistically significant at the 0.05 significant level.

The Residuals vs Fitted plot show that the variance is not constant for this model, therefore this regression isn’t the greatest because there are so many non-significant variables. However, the Q-Q plot does show signs of being normally distributed. The residual plot shows that there are no major outliers (high leverage and high residuals). Overall, there are mixed signs of the linearity of this model. We do have to keep in mind that there are a lot of statistically insignificant variables, which does alter the performance of the regression.

Discussion

Our Fisher’s test and regression analysis show that there are some significant relationships between the violent conflict events (in the conflict datasets), to the number of detainees by township. These relationships are not consistent, meaning that not all conflict event types are statistically significant in these analyses. Our regressions did show that an increase in the population size resulted in a decrease in the number of detainees per 1000 of population. This suggests that smaller townships are facing more political violence from various agents, and those populations are facing higher rates of detainment. It is interesting to note that the number of detainments was the highest earlier in the year, but the number of conflicts was at its peak in the last few months of the year. One potential alternative analysis that we could run in the future is if there is a correlation, by month, on the number of deadly conflicts, by the number of detainees.

This situation in Myanmar is politically sensitive. The human rights violations are extremely concerning, and the lives lost are saddening. However, we have to recognize that the scale at which this information is relevant can only come at the international level. Accountability on the international stage will be crucial so that the people who have been directly and indirectly affected by the mass violence in Myanmar for the past year can begin to heal. This data can help with potential international intervention in the region. Although we focused this analysis at the township level, regional level analysis could be useful to identify regions in dire need. This could be an opportunity for humanitarian aid in these regions from neighboring countries in Southeast Asia, international organizations like the United Nations, or other human rights organizations.

This data was challenging to navigate. The pros and cons of real-world data were very evident. Although thorough in some ways, doing a township-level analysis highlighted some of the data consistency issues with these datasets. For example, factors like age were missing in most datasets, with the exception of the fallen dataset. This was challenging because our group thought it would be an interesting idea to study if there was a generational difference in political activism. However, we we’re unable to use just the fallen dataset because it felt incomplete to the entire dataset. We only looked at one aspect of the MIMU dataset (population). One of the potential visualizations we were thinking about doing was a population pyramid of Myanmar according to gender and different age brackets. If we had robust age data, then this would be interesting to use in the analysis. The apply_leven function was helpful in mapping townships, but it was limited because of the way that certain townships/addresses were recorded. For example, the first detainee was the infamous Aung San Suu Kyi, however her township was not mapped by the apply_leven function and she remained out of our joined data. One positive of this dataset was that we were able to extract a large enough sample (greater than 30) for the townships that did map correctly.

Conclusion

The situation in Myanmar is quite concerning. The increase in the number of conflicts instigated by the military increased towards the end of the year, and the number of detainees was high at the beginning of the year. Although data can give us some understanding and insight to the situation, it is not perfect. This data may not be perfectly representative of the violence that Burmese peoples have faced (and are facing) for this past year. Our data is imperfect, but is indicative of real-world scenarios. Although our tests and regressions we’re not statistically significant for all variables (conflict types, population etc.), they were somewhat informative on the levels of violence occurring at the township level. Potential alternate/further analyses that we suggest are a regional level, and age analysis to help understand the multitude of aspects in this situation.
